C language regression tests (SDCC)
===================================

These tests verify that C source files compile correctly with the SDCC
compiler that MCU 8051 IDE drives on Windows via startsdcc.bat.

Unlike the assembler tests (which use the IDE's built-in --assemble CLI),
C compilation is delegated to the external SDCC toolchain. These tests
therefore drive SDCC directly, the same way the IDE does.

Test cases (testcases/):
  001_minimal.c        - Minimal program (empty main + infinite loop)
  002_io_ports.c       - SFR/port access, bit operations
  003_functions.c      - Functions, parameters, arithmetic
  004_arrays_structs.c - Arrays, structs, pointers
  005_interrupts.c     - ISRs (__interrupt), timers, volatile

Each test case has:
  NNN_name.c        - C source file
  NNN_name.ihx.exp  - Expected Intel HEX output (baseline from SDCC 4.5.0)

Verification strategy:
  The runner (run_tests.ps1) compiles each .c file with SDCC and checks:
    1. SDCC exits 0 (compilation succeeds)
    2. A non-empty .ihx Intel HEX file is generated
    3. The .ihx record structure is valid

  NOTE: Exact .ihx byte content varies between SDCC versions and
  optimization settings, so the runner does NOT require a byte-exact
  match against .ihx.exp by default. The .exp files are kept as a
  reference baseline for manual inspection. Use --strict-hex to enable
  byte-exact comparison when validating against a pinned SDCC version.

Requirements:
  SDCC must be installed. The runner auto-detects it in:
    - System PATH
    - C:\Program Files\SDCC\bin
    - C:\Program Files (x86)\SDCC\bin
    - D:\Program Files\SDCC\bin
  The SDCC bin directory is prepended to PATH during the test so the
  sdcc subprocess (sdcpp/cc1) can be found.
